article.headline: San Francisco 76, Ohio State 65
article.story: SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Tyrone Riley scored 19 points as the University of San Francisco never trailed in its 76-65 upset of Ohio State. The Buckeyes' sophomore transfer J.J. Sullinger led all players with 24 points, and his junior transfer teammate Tony Stockman added another 22. However, no other Ohio State player scored more than seven points, while four Dons finished in double figures. USF's win was even more impressive considering it was without All-West Coast Conference guard John Cox, who will miss four to six weeks with a muscle strain suffered in the team's season opening win over Tennessee Martin. Also injured in that contest, James Bayless was a game-time decision for the Dons last night, but posted 11 points in 34 minutes of play. Filling in for Cox, USF's Jovan Harris provided an all-around effort with 11 points, nine rebounds and five assists, while Alvin Broussard finished with 14 points on a 4-for-5 performance from three-point range. The Buckeyes were clearly out of sync in their first game of the season, shooting only 12-of-26 from the free-throw line and turning the ball over 18 times. Ohio State went on a 10-0 run early in the second half to pull within three, but that would prove as close as it would come. After falling behind by seven with less than four minutes to play, Buckeyes head coach Jim O'Brien received his second technical and was ejected. Ohio State will play three more games on the road before heading home. Last night's game marked the first time the two basketball programs ever met.
